    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About L-Theanine Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What does L-theanine do?</summary>
      <p>L-theanine is an amino acid found primarily in green tea that promotes relaxation without causing drowsiness. It works by increasing alpha brain wave activity — the same brain state associated with meditation — within 30-40 minutes of ingestion. L-theanine also modulates levels of GABA, serotonin, and dopamine, which are neurotransmitters that regulate mood, focus, and stress response. A 2019 randomized controlled trial in <em>Nutrients</em> found that 200mg of L-theanine daily for four weeks significantly reduced stress-related symptoms and improved cognitive function in healthy adults.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much L-theanine should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>Most clinical studies use doses between 100mg and 400mg per day, with 200mg being the most commonly studied and recommended amount for stress relief and focus. For sleep support, doses of 200-400mg taken 30-60 minutes before bedtime have shown efficacy in clinical trials. L-theanine has an excellent safety profile with no established upper limit, though most experts recommend staying within the 100-400mg range for daily use. Unlike many supplements, L-theanine shows noticeable effects within 30-60 minutes of ingestion.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take L-theanine with caffeine?</summary>
      <p>Yes, and this is one of the most well-studied nootropic combinations in the world. L-theanine combined with caffeine has been shown to improve attention, task switching, and accuracy while reducing the jittery side effects of caffeine alone. A 2008 study in <em>Nutritional Neuroscience</em> found that 97mg of L-theanine with 40mg of caffeine significantly improved accuracy during demanding cognitive tasks. The typical recommended ratio is 2:1 (L-theanine to caffeine), so 200mg of L-theanine with 100mg of caffeine — roughly one cup of coffee.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does L-theanine make you sleepy?</summary>
      <p>L-theanine does not cause drowsiness or sedation at standard doses. Unlike melatonin or valerian root, L-theanine promotes relaxation through alpha brain wave enhancement rather than through sedative pathways. This means you can take it during the day for calm focus without impaired alertness. However, when taken before bedtime, L-theanine can improve sleep quality by reducing anxiety and mental chatter that interfere with sleep onset. The effect is context-dependent: it calms an overactive mind but does not force sleepiness in an alert person.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for L-theanine to work?</summary>
      <p>L-theanine typically produces noticeable effects within 30-60 minutes of ingestion. EEG studies have detected increased alpha brain wave activity as early as 30 minutes after a 200mg dose. The calming effect generally peaks at 60-90 minutes and can last for 3-5 hours depending on the dose and individual metabolism. This relatively fast onset makes L-theanine one of the more immediately perceptible supplements, unlike minerals like magnesium that require weeks of consistent use to improve baseline status.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is L-theanine safe to take every day?</summary>
      <p>L-theanine is classified as Generally Recognized as Safe (GRAS) by the FDA and has an excellent safety profile in clinical research. Studies lasting up to 8 weeks with daily doses of 200-400mg have reported no significant adverse effects. L-theanine does not cause dependency, tolerance, or withdrawal symptoms, which distinguishes it from pharmaceutical anxiolytics and sleep medications. However, individuals taking blood pressure medications or stimulant drugs should consult their healthcare provider, as L-theanine may have additive effects with these medications.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between L-theanine and melatonin for sleep?</summary>
      <p>L-theanine and melatonin work through completely different mechanisms. Melatonin is a hormone that signals to your body that it is time to sleep by binding to melatonin receptors in the brain. It directly influences circadian rhythm timing and sleep onset. L-theanine is an amino acid that promotes relaxation by increasing alpha brain waves and modulating GABA, serotonin, and dopamine. It helps quiet mental chatter and reduce anxiety that prevents sleep, but it does not directly trigger sleepiness. Sleep experts often recommend L-theanine for people whose insomnia is driven by racing thoughts, and melatonin for those with circadian rhythm disruption such as jet lag or shift work.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are L-theanine gummies as effective as capsules?</summary>
      <p>L-theanine gummies can be equally effective as capsules when they contain an equivalent dose. The amino acid L-theanine is stable across delivery formats and does not require specific absorption conditions like fat-soluble vitamins. The primary consideration is the dose per serving — some gummies provide only 50-100mg per serving compared to 200mg in most capsules, so you may need to take two gummies to match a single capsule dose. The trade-off is that gummies contain added sugar and flavoring, while capsules are typically cleaner formulations. For compliance and daily habit formation, gummies offer a meaningful advantage.</p>
    </details>

